ctions between images, bodies, and text. Drawing on a range of methodological approaches, including literary analysis and history, linguistics, ethics, and queer, cultural, and film studies, Sanchez sheds new light on texts by T.S. Eliot, Ezra Pound, Gertrude Stein, William Carlos Williams, Charlie Chaplin, and many others. By approaching modernism through the perspective of Deaf and disability studies, Deafening Modernism reconceptualizes deafness as a critical modality enabling us to freshly engage topics we thought we knew.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-SA 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/4.0  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aLanguage and languages in literature. 0aModernism (Literature)xUnited StatesxUnited States. 0aModernism (Literature)zUnited States. 0aVisual poetry, AmericanxHistory and criticism. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Sociology / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertNew York University Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311072899640uhttps://doi.org/10.18574/nyu/9781479828869.001.0001zOpen Access7040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781479810628zOpen Access70423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781479810628/original  a978-3-11-072899-6 New York University Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-GOA